'''HMS ''Bristol''''' was the [[name ship]] of [[Bristol-class frigate|her class]] of wooden [[screw frigate]]s built for the [[Royal Navy]] during the 1860s.

==Design and description==
''Bristol'' was {{convert|250|ft|m|1}} [[Length between perpendiculars|long between perpendiculars]] and {{convert|214|ft|7|in|m|1}} at the [[keel]]. She had a [[beam (nautical)|beam]] of {{convert|52|ft|m|1}}, a [[Draft (hull)|draught]] of {{convert|18|ft|10|in|m|1}} at [[deep load]] and a depth of [[hold (ship)|hold]] of {{convert|18|ft|8|in|m|1}}. The ship's [[tonnage]] was 3,027 <small>{{fraction|26|94}}</small> tons [[Builder's Old Measurement|burthen]] and ''Bristol'' displaced {{convert|4023|LT|t}}. The ship had a crew of 550 officers and [[naval rating|ratings]].<ref name=w7>Winfield, pp. 478–80</ref>

She had a horizontal, two-cylinder, [[Marine steam engine#Simple expansion|single-expansion steam engine]], built by [[Robert Napier (engineer)|Robert Napier & Sons]], that drove a single [[propeller shaft]] using steam that was provided by four [[boiler]]s. The engine produced {{convert|2088|ihp|lk=in}} which gave the ship a maximum speed of {{convert|11.8|kn|lk=in}} under steam. To improve her sailing qualities, the propeller could be hoisted into the hull.<ref name=w7/>

''Bristol'' was initially equipped with thirty [[ML 8 inch shell gun|ML eight-inch (203&nbsp;mm)]] [[British ordnance terms#SBML|smoothbore muzzle-loading guns (SBML)]] of 65 [[hundredweight]] on her [[gundeck]]. These guns were designed specifically to fire the latest exploding shells, unlike the traditional solid cannonballs. On her [[Deck (ship)#Upper deck|upper deck]] were twenty 32-pounder SBML guns that weighed 56 hundredweight and a single [[68-pounder gun|68-pounder]] SBML gun on a [[pivot gun|pivot mount]]. In January 1868, the ship was rearmed with 10 eight-inch shell guns and a dozen [[Muzzle-loading rifle|rifled, muzzle-loading]] [[RML 64 pounder 71 cwt gun|64-pounder guns]] on the gundeck. Four more 64-pounders were mounted on the upper deck.<ref>Winfield, p. 478</ref>

'An analysis of ship air and its effect' was made and reported during a four months' voyage (July to November 1871) from the Cape of Good Hope to England. This gives an insite to the conditions on board and concludes 'Seamen, as a body, are neither healthy nor long lived, but the reverse. This is proved, first, by their low average age, said to be 33'. A description of the ship layout is also given, the upper tier contained the Main deck, Upper, Half deck, Study, Mess room & Main deck cabins. Middle tier contained the Lower deck, Steerage, Ward room, Chest (cadets' sleeping)room and steerage cabins Do., & Pantry. The Lowest tier Stokehole, Engine room, Screw alley, Cockpit, Store room & Cells. It also states the ship had four boilers.<ref>{{cite journal | url = http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1988910/pdf/medcht00004-0221.pdf | pmc=1988910 | pmid=20896400 | volume=56 | title=An Analysis of Ship Air and its Effects | year=1873 | journal=Med Chir Trans | pages=157–188.1 | last1 = Rattray | first1 = A}}</ref>

==Construction and career==
''Bristol'', named after the [[Bristol|city of Bristol]], was ordered on 9 April 1856 as part of the 1856 Naval Programme. As the design was revised several times, she was not [[keel laying|laid down]] at [[Woolwich Dockyard]] until 16 September 1859. The ship was [[Ceremonial ship launching|launched]] on 12 February 1861, but she was not [[Ship commissioning|commissioned]] until October 1865.<ref name=w7/>

